{{Infobox language | name = Daga | states = [[Papua New Guinea]] | region = [[Milne Bay Province]] | ethnicity = | speakers = 9,000 | date = 2007 | ref = e18 | familycolor = Papuan | fam1 = [[Trans–New Guinea languages|Trans–New Guinea]] | fam2 = [[Dagan languages|Dagan]] | fam3 = Daga–Mapena? | iso3 = dgz | glotto = daga1275 | glottorefname = Daga }}Daga (Dimuga, Nawp) is a non-Austronesian language of Papua New Guinea. Daga is spoken by about 9,000 people as of 2007.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ethnologue.com/18/language/dgz/|title=Daga|work=Ethnologue|access-date=2018-11-15|language=en}}</ref> The peoples that speak Daga are located in the [[Rabaraba]] subdistrict of [[Milne Bay Province|Milne Bay district]], and in the [[Abau District|Abau subdistrict]] of the [[Central Province (Papua New Guinea)|Central district]] of [[Papua New Guinea]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|title=Daga Grammar|last=Murane|first=Elizabeth|publisher=Benjamin F, Ulson|year=1974|isbn=|location=University of Oklahoma|pages=1-20}}</ref>
== Speakers == The people who speak Daga live in the Rabaraba subdistrict of the Milne Bay Province on Papua New Guinea. This province is about 5,405.4 sq mi (14,000km<sup>2</sup>) with a population of 209,054 people. The [[File:Papua_new_guinea_provinces_(numbers)_2012.png|thumb|266x266px|The Milne Bay Province is illustrates in section 10.]] Economy of the province is brought by tourism, palm oil, and gold mining on [[Misima Island]].
During [[World War II]], the [[Battle of Milne Bay]] took place in the province giving it some other significance.
The [[Massim]], the people of Milne Bay, have exchanged culture with nearby islands and gained many rituals from nearby including the [[Kula ring]]. The people of the Massim are characterized by [[Matrilineality|matrilineal]] descent.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pcabii.org/resources/provinces/Milne%20Bay%20Province.pdf|title=Milne Bay Province|last=|first=|date=|website=http://pcabii.org/resources/provinces/Milne%20Bay%20Province.pdf|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>
The people of Milne Bay while distinct from, are still in culture sync with Papua New Guinea. The remote, wild, and pristine lands of Papua New guinea holds a lot of diversity. There are over 7000 different cultures in Papua New Guinea although there is only about 7 million people living there.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.zegrahm.com/blog/papua-new-guinea-culture-introduction-ancient-traditions|title=Papua New Guinea Culture: An Introduction to Ancient Traditions|work=Zegrahm Expeditions|access-date=2018-11-16|language=en}}</ref> The people of Papua New Guinea have strong ties to music having spontaneous and coordinated acts of musical expression throughout the year.
== Phonology == Daga has thirteen consonants and five vowels.<ref name=":0" /> {| class="wikitable" |+Vowel Phonemes ! ![[Front vowel|Front]] ![[Back vowel|Back]] |- |[[Close vowel|Close]] |i |u |- |[[Mid vowel|Mid]] | |o |- |[[Open vowel|Open]] |e |a |} {| class="wikitable" |+Consonant Phonemes ! ![[Bilabial consonant|Bilabial]] !Bilabial Rounded ![[Labiodental consonant|Labiodental]] ![[Dental consonant|Dental]] ![[Alveolar consonant|Alveolar]] ![[Velar consonant|Velar]] |- |[[Stop consonant|Stop]] |p b | | |t |d |k g |- |[[Nasal consonant|Nasal]] |m | | | |n | |- |[[Semivowel]] | |w | | | |y |- |[[Lateral consonant|Lateral]] | | | | | |r |- |[[Fricative consonant|Fricative]] | | |v | |s | |}
== Grammar ==
=== Morphemes === In Daga, there are some rules for how to make morphemes. some include, the ending of [[Word stem|stems]] other than G, R, S, and W add /a/ if the next suffix is a [[Suffix|consonant-initial suffix]]. If the final consonant of a [[prefix]] is before a consonant-initial stem, the [[manner of articulation]] of the final [[consonant]] of the prefix is changed to match the manner of articulation of the initial consonant of the stem. When the [[morpheme]] has initial [[phoneme]] /w/ is comes before the vowel /o/ or /u/, the /w/ is lost in the final word. When the final phoneme of a preceding morpheme and the initial phoneme of a following morpheme are both [[Vowel|vowels]], the initial-vowel of the following morpheme is lost unless that phoneme is /i/, in which case it is left as is. For all [[Noun|nouns]], the final vowel is -e.
=== Morphophonology === When the consonants G, R, S, and W end a stem or suffix they have a phoneme change based on the following phoneme.<ref name=":0" /> {| class="wikitable" |+ ![[Morpheme]] !Followed by /i/ or /e/ !Followed by /a/, /o/, or /u/ !Followed by [[Consonant]] ![[Final-obstruent devoicing|Word Final]] |- |g |g |g | --- |k |- |r |r |r |ra |t |- |s |s |t | --- |t |- |w |v |w |wa |o |} This rule has exceptions for these three words: {| class="wikitable" |+ |unuG | -nege | -en |ununegen |- |yagiR | -nege | -iwan |yaginegiwan |- |ewaS | -nege | -en |ewanegen |}
=== Stems === In Daga, word [[Word stem|stems]] are the part of the word that gives the word meaning. Compound word stems are often a verb stem followed by a combination of the verb yaw ("see") .
<big>wa ('say') + yaw ('see') = wayaw ('ask')</big>
This works with all verb stems and completely changes the meaning of the verb stem. [[Verb stem|Prefix-derived verb stems]] are verb stems that follow one of four prefixes, wa-, to-, en-, and a-. These prefixes are used to classify the verb stem to identify a certain thing or group of thing. The prefix wa- on a verb stem makes the verb stem only apply to one subject. The prefix to- means that the verb will be changed to involve hitting a singular subject. The prefix en- means the action depicted by the verb is changed to match an action that involves sticking into an object. The prefix a- also adjusts the verb stem to involve biting. Adjective-derived verb stems are verbs that are created by using an adjective stem and verbalization to create a verb out of an adjective. For example, the word ''tama ('straight')'' followed by the verbalization ''-am'' creates an outcome of the word ''tamanam'' ('correct'). There are also noun-derived verb stems which like adjective-derived verb stems use a verbalization and a noun stem to create a verb from a noun. An example of this is when the word ''ago'' ('servant') with the verbalization ''-at'' becomes ''agat'' ('help'). This concept of deriving words from other stems of other classifications also carries across to nouns and adjectives, where Daga has verb-derived noun stems which is when a verb can be nominalized by the suffix ''-at'' and becomes a noun. Although the stems give meaning to the word, the word isn't complete without a suffix.<ref name=":0" />
=== Words === In Daga, like many other languages has many different classifications of words. [[Clitic|Clitics]] in Daga is a classification of word which can then be classified again down into 3 more classes, location clitics which describe are used to illustrate location of a noun, substantive clitics which are the last word in a substantive clause or a [[Nominalize|nominalized]] clause, and included-clause clitics are used to complete clauses using homophuous medical suffixes. Postpositions are a classification of words that are similar in their manner of usage as that of a clitic in which it is used to mark location, accompaniment, comparison, and temporal construction. Positionals can also be used with personal markers to give location or demonstrate accompaniment alongside a person.<ref name=":0" /> {| class="wikitable" |+Person Markers ! !Singluar !Plural |- |1 | -ma | -nu |- |2 | -ga | -ya |- |3 |# | -mu |}
=== Phrases === Long phrases are extremely uncommon in Daga.
In Daga, there are two [[Intensifier|intensifiers]], ''di'' which is used with any phrase to add emphasis, and ''iren'' is used after a noun, adjective, and positional to add specificity. Conjunctions are used to join phrases, clauses, and sentences. The conjunctions that do these things can be considered different classifications. {| class="wikitable" |+Conjunctions !Phrase !Clause !Temporal !English |- |ge |e/si/di | |and |- |go/o |go/o | |or |- | |menan/gapan/anega | |therefore |- | |iwa | |because |- | |go/ae | |but |- | |mini/umap | |like |- | |anega | |likewise |- | | |boge |immediately |- | | |gatawan |later |- | | |amba |then |- | | |evi |later |}
=== Interrogatives === Daga uses ''ya'' as a prefix to illustrate negative [[tagmeme]] of the normal verb phrases, and ''uon'' to illustrate negative tagmeme of a summary, sentence, conversational, response, or interrogative.<ref name=":0" /> [[Interrogatives]] in Daga are illustrated by the elongation of the final syllable along with an initial word to start the clause: {| class="wikitable" |+Interrogatives |dime |why |- |dim |what |- |ansena |which |- |anena |how |- |andi |when |- |amba |where |- |animpo |how many |- |da |who |}
=== Numbers === Numeral roots in Daga are created using an odd system. Daga only has the numbers 1, 2, 3, 4, and 10 and use the convention of using body-parts to represent numbers. For example, the word ''nani'' ('hand') means five and the word ''apen'' ('man') means 20 counting all the fingers and toes attached to that entity. These words along with the word ''yamu'' ('other') creates the phrases that illustrate numbers.<ref name=":0" /> {| class="wikitable" |+Numbers and Numerical phrases !Number !Daga !English |- |1 |da |one |- |2 |de |two |- |3 |yampo |three |- |4 |degede |four |- |10 |aonugaet |ten |- | |iravi |all |- | |aruga |many |- | |da de |few (one or two) |}
