{{Infobox writer | name=Dhiru Parikh | image=Dhiru Parikh.JPG | img_capt= | caption = Parikh in 2013 | birth_name =Dhiru Ishwarlal Parikh | birth_date={{birth date and age|1933|8|31|df=y}} | birth_place=[[Viramgam]], [[Gujarat]] | death_date= | death_place= | occupation= poet, critic, story writer | period= | language = [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]] | nationality= Indian | spouse= {{marriage|Kamla Parikh|1964}} | signature= Dhiru Parikh signature.png | awards={{plainlist| * [[Kumar Chandrak]] (1971) * [[Ranjitram Suvarna Chandrak]] (2008)}} |module = {{Listen |embed= yes|filename=Voice of Dhiru Parikh.ogg |title= Dhiru Parikh's voice |description=Speech on 'Town and Town Poetry'}} {{Infobox academic | doctoral_students = [[Praful Raval]] }} }}
'''Dhiru Ishwarlal Parikh''' (born 31 August 1933) is [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]] poet, short story writer and critic from India. He is an editor of [[Kavilok]] and [[Kumar magazine|Kumar]], a Gujarati literary magazines.
==Life== [[File:School of Languages in Gujarat University Ahmedabad.jpg|thumb|The School of Languages where Parikh served as professor and head of Gujarati department]] Dhiru Parikh was born on 31 August 1933 at [[Viramgam]] near [[Ahmedabad]], [[Gujarat]], India. He completed his [[matriculation]] in 1951 from the town. He completed B.A. in 1955 from L. D. Arts College, M.A. in 1958 from [[Gujarat University]] and awarded Ph.D. in 1967 for his thesis, ''Rasyugma Prakruti Nirupan''. Since 1955, he teaches at C. U. Shah College. He served as the principal of Mahila Arts College of [[Wadhwan]] affiliated with [[SNDT Women's University]] from 1967 to 1969. Later he joined as a professor of Department of Gujarati, School of Languages, Gujarat University in 1977, served as a head from 1986 to his retirement in 1993. He edits bimonthly, ''[[Kavilok]]'' of Gujarati poetry, since 1976 which he joined in 1969 as co-editor. He served as president of [[Gujarati Sahitya Parishad]] from December 2013 to December 2014. He also edits ''[[Kumar magazine|Kumar]]'' since 1991.<ref name=AGSI>{{cite book|title=અર્વાચીન ગુજરાતી સાહિત્યનો ઈતિહાસ - આધુનિક અને અનુઆધુનિક યુગ (History of Modern Gujarati Literature – Modern and Postmodern Era)|first=Prasad|last=Brahmabhatt |publisher=Parshwa Publication|location=Ahmedabad|year=2010|pages=320–322|language=gu|isbn=978-93-5108-247-7}}</ref><ref name=dgy>{{cite news|url=http://deshgujarat.com/2013/12/24/dhirubhai-parikh-becomes-new-president-of-gujarati-sahitya-parishad/ |title=Dhirubhai Parikh becomes new President of Gujarati Sahitya Parishad|date=December 24, 2013|work=DeshGujarat|accessdate =May 10, 2014}}</ref><ref name=gsp>{{cite web|url=http://www.gujaratisahityaparishad.com/prakashan/sarjako/savishesh/Savishesh-Dhiru-Parikh.html|title=Dhirubhai Parikh|language =Gujarati |publisher=[[Gujarati Sahitya Parishad]]|accessdate =28 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://m.timesofindia.com/city/ahmedabad/Master-of-metre/articleshow/21889395.cms|title=Master of metre|first=Saeed|last=Khan|publisher=[[The Times of India]]|date=18 August 2013|accessdate=28 March 2015}}</ref>
He married Kamla Parikh, born Kamla Patel, in 1964.<ref>{{cite magazine|editor-last=Rye|editor-first=Madhu|editor-link=Madhu Rye|title=Kantak Ni Khushboo (Short story by Dhiru Parikh)|magazine=Mamta|date=December 2017|location=New Jersey|publisher=Chandramani Prakashan|page=15}}</ref>
==Works== His first work published in 1951 was a short story titled ''Pehlu Rudan''. His short story collection ''Kantakni Khushbo'' (1964) has twenty two stories. His another story collection is ''Parajit Vijay''. ''Ughad'' (1979) is a collection of poetry. ''Ang Pachisi'' (1982) is a collection of twenty five traditional ''[[Chhappa]]'' styled sarcastic poems. ''Aagiya'' (1982) is a collection of [[Haiku]]s. his other poetry collections are ''Hari Chadya Adfete'', ''Shikhare Betha Sthitipragnya'' (2003), ''Station ane Train'' (2007).<ref name=gsp/><ref name=AGSI/>
He wrote biography of [[Rajendra Shah]] under ''Gujarati Granthkar Shreni'' and published in 1977. '' Rasyug ma Prakritinirupan'' (Nature in medieval literature of Raas, 1978) is his research thesis. ''Atratya Tatratya'' (1978) is a collection of introductory essays on poets which include Gujarati poets along with C. K. Louis, [[W. H. Auden]], [[Pablo Neruda]], [[Eugenio Montale]] and [[Yevgeny Yevtushenko]]. ''Narsinh Mehta'' (1981) is a biography of [[Narsinh Mehta]]. ''Kharakshar'' (1982) has short introduction of several Gujarati authors including [[Dayaram]], [[Dalpatram]], [[Narmad]], [[Priyakant Maniyar]], [[Jagdish Joshi (poet)|Jagdish Joshi]], [[Manilal Desai]]. ''Kaalma Korya Naam'' (1977) is a collection of short biographies including [[Yasunari Kawabata]], [[Ishwar Chandra Vidyasagar]], [[Charles Dickens]], [[Dalpatram]], [[Pujya Mota]].<ref name=gsp/><ref name=AGSI/>
''Samkalin Kavio'' (1983) is criticism of poetry of contemporary poets including [[Labhshankar Thakar]], [[Sitanshu Yashaschandra]], [[Rajendra Shukla]], [[Ravji Patel]], [[Adil Mansuri]]. ''Paravartan'' (1985), ''Prayogshil Sarjak Nhanalal'' (1987), ''Amar Brahmana Alokma'', ''Ubhayanvaya'' (1986) are works of criticism. He edited several books ''Nishkulanand Padavali'' (1981), ''Saar Mahakavyo'' (1983), ''Panch Mahakavyo'' (1984) and ''[[T. S. Eliot]]'' (1989). ''Tulnatmak Sahitya'' (1984) is a work on [[comparative literature]]. He translated ''[[Divine Comedy]]'' in 1985.<ref name=gsp/><ref name=AGSI/>
==Awards== He was awarded [[Kumar Chandrak]] in 1971, Swami Sachchidanand Sanman in 2004, [[Premanand Suvarna Chandrak]] in 2006 and [[Ranjitram Suvarna Chandrak]] in 2008.<ref name=AGSI/><ref name=dgy/><ref name=gsp/>
