'''M. Venkatakrishnaiah''' (1844–1933) was pioneer of [[journalism]], author, [[Social Reformer|social reformer]], educator, civil servant and [[Philanthropy|philanthropist]] based in the city of [[Mysore]], [[India]].<ref name="hindu remembrance">{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-karnataka/article616950.ece|title=Venkatakrishnaiah remembered|date=6 September 2010|accessdate=3 April 2012|newspaper=The Hindu}}</ref><ref name="website bio">{{cite web|url=http://www.mysorethathayya.org/biography.html|title=Vruddhapitamaha, Dayasagara Sri M. Venkatakrishnaiah – A Man with many Dimensions|accessdate=3 April 2012}}</ref> He was often referred to as the grand-old man of [[Mysore]] or Tataiah.<ref name="hindu remembrance"/> His achievements contributed immensely towards Mysore's notability as a famed center of education and [[model city]]. He wrote and published a series of [[newspaper]]s such as the Hita Bodhini (1883), Sadhvi (1899), Vrittanta Chintamani (1885), Mysore Herald, Poura Samajika Patrike, Mysore Patriot, Mysore Review, Wealth of Mysore, Nature Cure and Sampadabhyudaya.<ref name="hindu remembrance"/>

